competition-message: In the picture, the page specifically designated for the check-in with the date must be visible. Printed or visible on a computer, phone. THREE full-length pictures: from the front, the side, and the back. Try to ensure the pictures are taken with the camera directly facing you and in good lighting, with a neutral background, full-length, standing straight, not trying to “stick out your bottom” or push out your stomach, without filters! It's impossible for me to assess your progress if the pictures are of poor quality, dark, taken at an angle, etc. Selfies - NO.

plan_gym_week_1: As these are the first two weeks, and you need to get used to the load, the number of repetitions will often be 15 or more. The first two weeks are intended for endurance training and mastering movements. If it seems difficult, perform exercises without weights. Keep the number of repetitions unchanged. Pay attention to what needs to be done in a superset (same letters) and what needs to be done separately. If you find specific exercises too challenging, you can choose to replace them with other variations.

plan_gym_week_3: These two weeks are intended for you to develop your strength and find the right working weight for exercises. The average number of repetitions here is 10-12, with 3-4 sets. Remember - follow your fitness level and be careful not to overstrain, but also try not to spare yourself too much because these two weeks are meant for putting in a strong effort. Warm-up/cool-down clips are not added anymore; you already know what needs to be done at the beginning and end of each workout. ABS exercises and cardio according to your own discretion.

Warm-up/ABS exercises/cardio according to your own discretion.

plan_home_week_1: In the first two weeks, the program will be based on interval training and supersets. In one superset (small circuit), there will be 3 exercises, each lasting 45 seconds with a 15-second rest break between them. So, you'll perform exercise B1 for 45 seconds and then move on to the next (with a 15-second rest), and so on, completing B2 and B3. After finishing one superset, take a rest of 60-120 seconds and start the B circuit again from the beginning (3 sets in total, so 3 circuits). Keep in mind that when training at home, you may not have a wide range of equipment. If the 45:15 interval is too challenging, you can use a 30:15 interval. Be creative and find ways to make exercises easier or more challenging based on your fitness level. Use dumbbells, bars, water bottles, bags, resistance bands, etc.! ABS exercises - adapt them to your needs and posibilities if the given ones are not good for you.
plan_home_week_2: In the first two weeks, the program will be based on interval training and supersets. After finishing one superset, take a rest of 60-120 seconds and start the B circuit again from the beginning (3 sets in total, so 3 circuits). Keep in mind that when training at home, you may not have a wide range of equipment. If the 45:15 interval is too challenging, you can use a 30:15 interval. Be creative and find ways to make exercises easier or more challenging based on your fitness level. Use dumbbells, bars, water bottles, bags, resistance bands, etc.! ABS exercises - adapt them to your needs and posibilities if the given ones are not good for you.
plan_home_week_3: These two weeks are designed for you to develop your strength and endurance. You will no longer work with intervals but focus on repetitions. The average number of repetitions here ranges from 10 to 15. If 3 sets seem too few, you can do 4. Remember - follow your fitness level and be careful not to overstrain, but also try not to spare yourself too much because these two weeks are meant for putting in a strong effort. If you have heavier dumbbells or bars at home, use them and perform fewest repetitions of the indicated. On the other hand, if you only have small or medium dumbbells at home, adjust the load by doing more repetitions.
